<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Slender leafhoppers, overall body coloration usually white to yellowish. Head as wide as pronotum, produced, crown convex. Forewing fourth apical cell short and third narrow. Hind wing submarginal vein complete, three apical cells. Pygofer with process. Aedeagus body elongate or robust usually with a pair of basal process.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dikrella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dikrella" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dikrella</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Kunzeana" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Kunzeana" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Kunzeana</taxonomicName>
Oman, 1940 by the distinctly widened basal part of the forewing inner apical cell.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Confined to the New World, recorded from: United States, Mexico, Costa Rica, Cuba, Puerto Rico, Panama, Canada, Ecuador, Colombia, Bolivia, and Brazil.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
